Toccoa is a city, and the [county seat](/County_seat) of [Stephens County](/Stephens_County,_Georgia), [Georgia](/Georgia_(U.S._state)), located in the [United States](/United_States). It’s situated in the state’s far northeast, brushing up against the border with [South Carolina](/South_Carolina). For context, it’s about 50 miles (80&#160;km) from [Athens](/Athens,_Georgia) and a somewhat longer haul, roughly 90 miles (140&#160;km) northeast of [Atlanta](/Atlanta). The census of 2020 reported a population of 9,133.

History

Toccoa, 1941

Before any European settlers arrived, the land that would become Toccoa was home to [Mississippian](/Mississippian_culture) and [Yuchi](/Yuchi) peoples. These groups were historically linked to the [Muscogee](/Muscogee) Creek confederacy, and later found themselves allied with the [Cherokee](/Cherokee). Their presence in the Tugaloo and Toccoa areas spanned over a millennium before colonization.

In 1957, Dr. Joseph Caldwell of the [University of Georgia](/University_of_Georgia) undertook salvage archaeological studies. This was a crucial effort, as the area was slated for flooding due to downstream dam construction. His findings indicated a settlement dating from approximately 800 to 1700 AD, culminating in the village's fiery destruction. At that time, it was inhabited by proto-Creek peoples, descendants of the Mississippian culture. Colonial maps, stretching up to the [American Revolution](/American_Revolutionary_War), identified this settlement as belonging to the Hogeloge people, a group now understood to be the [Yuchi](/Yuchi). Although they later allied with the Cherokee, their ethnic and linguistic origins were distinct.

Colonial period

"Saturday the 25th day of September 1725. About four of the Clock in the Afternoon came in the War hoop from Ouconey with a piece of a Scalp of one of the Enemies Scouts, giving an Accot that Scouts being in Number Twenty four that went out from old Estotoe, and Toxsoah having come upon the tracts of three of the Enemy found they were made downwards towards the other Towns (on wch) they Concluded to waylay the Path thinking by that means to Catch the Enemy being three in Number returning back to their old tracts near Estotoe from Town to Town."

George Chicken,&#32;Journal (quoted in Travels in the American Colonies )

Colonel George Chicken, an Indian agent, is credited with one of the earliest English colonial references to Toccoa. He documented it in his 1725 journal as Toxsoah. &#91;7&#93;

The [Unicoi Turnpike](/Unicoi_Turnpike), a significant [Native American](/Native_Americans_in_the_United_States) trading route, is known to have connected [Tennessee](/Tennessee) to [Savannah](/Savannah,_Georgia) via Toccoa as early as 1740. &#91;8&#93; &#91;9&#93; This path commenced on the [Savannah River](/Savannah_River), just downstream from where [Toccoa Creek](/Toccoa_Creek) enters it. &#91;10&#93; By 1830, the turnpike had been converted into a toll road. &#91;11&#93;

United States era

Following the [American Revolutionary War](/American_Revolutionary_War), Americans began to settle in the Toccoa region. The government, in lieu of payment owed to veterans, granted land. Colonel William H. Wofford led a group that relocated to the area after the war concluded. This settlement became known as Wofford's Tract, or Wofford's Settlement. Colonel Wofford himself is interred near [Toccoa Falls](/Toccoa_Falls). His son, [William T. Wofford](/William_T._Wofford), was born in the vicinity of Toccoa, which was then part of [Habersham County](/Habersham_County,_Georgia). Travelers at the time had to depend on fords and later ferries to cross the Tugaloo River. In 1804, James Jeremiah Prather constructed a swinging bridge, known as Prather's Bridge, but it was unfortunately swept away by a freshet, a sudden and significant rise in the river caused by heavy rainfall.

Georgia's [Land Lottery of 1820](/Georgia_Land_Lotteries) was conducted even though the Cherokee had not yet formally ceded this territory to the United States. Scots-Irish settlers, who acquired land through this lottery, migrated to the area from the backcountry of North Carolina and the Georgia coast. The [Georgia Gold Rush](/Georgia_Gold_Rush), which commenced in 1828, also drew a considerable number of new settlers to North Georgia. &#91;12&#93;

There was increasing pressure from Americans on the government to acquire the lands belonging to the Five Civilized Tribes, driven by a desire for cheaper land suitable for cotton plantations. The invention of the [cotton gin](/Cotton_gin), which revolutionized the processing of short-staple cotton, made its cultivation profitable in the upland regions like this one. At the behest of President [Andrew Jackson](/Andrew_Jackson), Congress enacted the [Indian Removal Act of 1830](/Indian_Removal_Act_of_1830). This legislation authorized the federal government to compel the cession of land from Southeastern tribes in exchange for territories west of the [Mississippi River](/Mississippi_River), in what became known as [Indian Territory](/Indian_Territory), now the state of Oklahoma. The forced [removal of the Cherokee](/Cherokee_removal) in 1838, a tragic event infamously known as the "[Trail of Tears](/Trail_of_Tears)," effectively extinguished most of their land claims to this region. The U.S. government subsequently opened former Cherokee and Creek ([Muscogee](/Muscogee)) lands for sale and American settlement. &#91;13&#93;

A more robust bridge was erected across the Tugaloo River in 1850. In that same year, James D. Prather oversaw the construction of his plantation house, named Riverside. It was situated on a hill offering commanding views of the upper [Tugalo River](/Tugalo_River). This Greek Revival [antebellum](/Antebellum_architecture) home was constructed by his enslaved African-American laborers, with timber sourced directly from his plantation. The Prather family cemetery was established to the right of the house.

During the [Civil War](/American_Civil_War), General [Robert Toombs](/Robert_Toombs), a close confidant of Prather, utilized Riverside as a sanctuary from pursuing Union troops. &#91;14&#93; The soldiers managed to reach the estate, &#91;15&#93; but Toombs eluded capture by hiding.

The Prather Bridge met its demise in 1863 when Confederate forces, during the Civil War, set it ablaze to prevent Union forces from crossing. James Jeremiah Prather and his son, James Devereaux Prather, took on the task of rebuilding the bridge in 1868. This iteration of the bridge stood until 1918, when it was again washed away. James D. Prather was responsible for its reconstruction in 1920. While a concrete bridge eventually replaced it, the original wooden structure was preserved as a local landmark. Tragically, it was destroyed by vandals in 1978.

Historical records indicate that the Johns House, a Victorian cottage located near Prather Bridge Road, was constructed in 1898. When the Georgia General Assembly officially established Stephens County in 1905, Toccoa was designated as the county seat. &#91;16&#93;

[President Franklin Delano Roosevelt](/President_Franklin_Delano_Roosevelt) made a visit to Toccoa on March 23, 1938, amidst the hardships of the [Great Depression](/Great_Depression). His train made a brief stop, during which he delivered remarks from the rear platform. His journey continued to [Gainesville](/Gainesville,_Georgia) for a significant speech, concluding with a vacation in [Warm Springs](/Warm_Springs,_Georgia). &#91;17&#93;

Nearby, [Camp Toccoa](/Camp_Toccoa) was established as a crucial [World War II](/World_War_II) [paratrooper](/Paratrooper) training facility. This camp served as the initial training ground for the [506th Parachute Infantry Regiment](/506th_Infantry_Regiment) of the Army's [101st Airborne Division](/101st_Airborne_Division). The exploits of its [Easy Company](/E_Company,_506th_Infantry_Regiment_(United_States)) became the subject of a celebrated non-fiction book and a subsequent HBO miniseries, both bearing the title [Band of Brothers](/Band_of_Brothers_(TV_miniseries)). &#91;18&#93;

Traveler's Rest

[Traveler's Rest](/Travelers_Rest_(Georgia)), an inn dating back to the 19th century and known locally as Jarrett Manor, is situated just outside Toccoa. It stands in proximity to [Lake Hartwell](/Lake_Hartwell), a body of water formed by the flooding of the [Tugaloo River](/Tugaloo_River) following the completion of the [Hartwell Dam](/Hartwell_Dam) in 1962. The inn has been recognized with the prestigious designation of [National Historic Landmark](/National_Historic_Landmark).

Toccoa Falls

[Toccoa Falls](/Toccoa_Falls), a natural waterfall plunging 186 feet (57 m), is located on the grounds of [Toccoa Falls College](/Toccoa_Falls_College). A short, gravel-paved path, approximately 100 yards long, provides easy access to the base of the falls.

Geography and climate

Toccoa is geographically located at 34°34′29″N 83°19′12″W&#xfeff; / &#xfeff;34.57472°N 83.32000°W&#xfeff; / 34.57472; -83.32000. &#91;19&#93;

According to data from the [United States Census Bureau](/United_States_Census_Bureau), the city encompasses a total area of 8.4 square miles (22&#160;km 2 ). Of this, 8.3 square miles (21&#160;km 2 ) is landmass, with a mere 0.1 square miles (0.26&#160;km 2 ), or 0.60%, being water.

The city's elevation stands at 313&#160;m (1,027&#160;ft).

Toccoa experiences a [humid subtropical climate](/Humid_subtropical_climate), which is characteristic of much of the state of [Georgia](/Georgia_(U.S._state)).

