The U.S. [2020 Census](/2020_United_States_census) documented Toccoa with a population of 9,133 residents, distributed across 3,359 households and 2,135 families.

2010 census

According to the 2010 census, Toccoa was home to 8,491 people. By July 2014, the estimated population had slightly decreased to 8,257. The median age for a Toccoa resident was 35.4 years. The city supported 1,135 companies. Educationally, 84.1% of residents held a high school diploma or higher. Toccoa comprised 4,009 housing units, with a median household income reported at $34,047. The foreign-born population numbered 213 individuals, and a significant 24.4% of the population lived below the poverty level. &#91;25&#93;

Economy

Shops in downtown Toccoa

Established in 1965, the Stephens County Development Authority (SCDA) has been instrumental in fostering and sustaining the economic growth of [Northeast Georgia](/Northeast_Georgia). &#91;26&#93; The SCDA focuses on attracting a diverse range of businesses, including industrial, manufacturing, distribution, corporate and regional headquarters, and customer service centers. &#91;27&#93; Its service area encompasses Toccoa and the surrounding communities of [Eastanollee](/Eastanollee,_Georgia), [Martin](/Martin,_Georgia), and [Avalon](/Avalon,_Georgia).

Key industrial zones within the region include the Toccoa Industrial Park, Meadowbrook Industrial Park, and Hayestone Brady Business Park. &#91;28&#93;

The primary employers in Stephens County, listed in descending order of size, are: the Stephens County School System, Caterpillar, Patterson Pump, ASI (GEM Industries), American Woodmark Corp., Standard Register, Sage Automotive Interiors, Habersham Plantation, Toccoa Falls College, Coats & Clark, Eaton Corporation, and PTL Company, a manufacturer of elevator fixtures and parts. &#91;29&#93; Notably, 1st Franklin Financial Corporation, a regional financial services company, was founded and is headquartered in Toccoa, employing over 1,300 individuals. &#91;30&#93;

Arts and culture

Annual events

The city's calendar is punctuated by a variety of annual events. These include the Currahee Military Weekend, the Ida Cox Music Series, Toast of Toccoa, Summer Movies at the Ritz, a Costume Parade, the Harvest Festival, ChristmasFest, and a Christmas Parade.

Music

Toccoa is home to a regional orchestra, the Toccoa Symphony Orchestra. &#91;31&#93; This ensemble is comprised of volunteer musicians drawn from the surrounding community, as well as from [South Carolina](/South_Carolina) and [Georgia](/Georgia_(U.S._state)). The symphony's mission is to provide access to high-quality symphonic music for the region and to serve as a gathering point for musicians from across northeast Georgia.

Founded in 1977 by Pinkie Craft Ware and Archie Sharretts, both esteemed music educators, the symphony has maintained a consistent performance schedule, presenting at least three concerts each season. It operates under the guidance of a board of directors and benefits from extensive support from its patrons.

The orchestra engages in collaborations with numerous musicians, offering a diverse array of concert experiences. The ensemble has had the honor of premiering works by emerging young composers, presents an annual Christmas concert featuring a choir of one hundred voices, &#91;32&#93; and provides opportunities for promising young performers from the nearby Toccoa Falls College to showcase their talents.

The rock band [Luxury](/Luxury_(Georgia_band)) also traces its origins to Toccoa, forming at Toccoa Falls College in the early 1990s.

Miles Through Time Automotive Museum

The Miles Through Time Automotive Museum, once a cooperative automotive exhibition space housed in a restored 1939 dealership, has since relocated to Clarkesville, GA, in Habersham County. &#91;33&#93; The museum showcases over a century of automotive history, with vehicles available for storage, consignment sale, or direct sale by owner. All displayed items are presented as museum exhibits.

Currahee Military Museum

The Currahee Military Museum, situated in downtown Toccoa at the original train station where arriving [GIs](/G.I._(military)) would disembark, is a tribute to the [paratroopers](/Paratrooper) of [World War II](/World_War_II) who underwent training at [Camp Toccoa](/Camp_Toccoa). This camp, formerly known as Camp Toombs, was located just outside the city, at the base of [Currahee Mountain](/Currahee_Mountain). The museum proudly houses the original [Aldbourne](/Aldbourne) stables, where [paratroopers](/Paratrooper) of the [101st Airborne Division](/101st_Airborne_Division) were temporarily quartered in England during 1944.

Only one structure from the original Camp Toccoa remains standing. This building, believed to have served as a food supply storage facility due to its location near the former camp's entrance and its foundational construction, was donated to the museum in 2011 by the Milliken company, which had been utilizing it as a machine shop. The museum harbors plans to restore this building, along with the surrounding grounds.

Annual Currahee Challenge

Held on the first Saturday of every October, the Currahee Challenge is a demanding six-mile race that follows the Colonel Sink Trail, the very path utilized by paratroopers during their combat training. It is widely regarded as one of the most challenging races in [America](/United_States). The race's unofficial motto encapsulates its difficulty: "Three Miles Up And Three Miles Down." This event is a cornerstone of the Currahee Military Weekend, a comprehensive commemoration that includes World War II [military reenactments](/Military_reenactment) staged in a simulated military camp, demonstrations of weaponry, book signings by veterans, a parade winding through the historic downtown district, a hangar dance held at the airport, and a special [banquet](/Banquet) featuring keynote speakers and esteemed veterans.

Ritz Theatre

The Ritz Theatre, a meticulously restored 1939 Art Deco movie palace, is a prominent feature of the Downtown Toccoa Historic District, located at 139 Doyle Street. It continues to serve as a vibrant venue for a wide array of entertainment.
