Education

Stephens County Schools

Stephens County Schools &#91;36&#93; provides educational services for students from preschool through the twelfth grade. The district encompasses four elementary schools, one middle school, and one high school. &#91;37&#93; The district employs 304 full-time teachers and serves a student population of over 4,405. &#91;38&#93;

Schools

*   Stephens County High School (SCHS) (grades 9–12)
*   Stephens County Fifth Grade Academy (located at SCMS) (grade 5)
*   Stephens County Middle School (SCMS) (grades 6–8)
*   Liberty Elementary (grades 1–2)
*   Toccoa Elementary (grades 3–4)
*   Big A Elementary (grades Pre K-K)

Stephens County High School completed the construction of its new facility in the spring of 2012. The modern building boasts a four-sided gymnasium arena, enhanced facilities for the fine arts, and an expanded media center.

Higher education

Toccoa is the home of [Toccoa Falls College](/Toccoa_Falls_College), a private Christian institution. Additionally, [North Georgia Technical College](/North_Georgia_Technical_College) operates its Currahee campus just south of Toccoa.

Infrastructure

Toccoa Amtrak Station
Construction of the Wells Viaduct over the North Broad River near Toccoa, 1901

Transportation

[Amtrak](/Amtrak)'s [Crescent](/Crescent_(Amtrak)) service provides connections for Toccoa to major cities including [New York](/New_York_City), [Philadelphia](/Philadelphia), [Baltimore](/Baltimore), [Washington](/Washington,_D.C.), [Charlotte](/Charlotte,_North_Carolina), [Atlanta](/Atlanta), [Birmingham](/Birmingham,_Alabama), and [New Orleans](/New_Orleans). The [Amtrak station](/Toccoa_(Amtrak_station)) is located at 47 North Alexander Street. This rail line is shared with the [Norfolk Southern Railway](/Norfolk_Southern_Railway). Prior to the establishment of Amtrak, Toccoa was a stop on the [Airline Belle](/Airline_Belle), a regional train operated by the [Southern Railway](/Southern_Railway_(U.S.)) from 1879 to 1931.

Toccoa also hosts the [Toccoa Airport](/Toccoa_Airport), a small executive airport situated to the northeast of the town. This airport was originally built by [R.G. LeTourneau](/R._G._LeTourneau) and is sometimes referred to as R.G. LeTourneau Field.

The nearest major highway is [Interstate 85](/Interstate_85). [State Route 17](/Georgia_State_Route_17) runs concurrently with an alternate route through the city while also bypassing Toccoa. [U.S. Route 123](/U.S._Route_123), also designated as [State Route 365](/Georgia_State_Route_365), passes directly through Toccoa.

Media

The local newspaper, [The Toccoa Record](/The_Toccoa_Record), was established in 1873.

Radio station [WNEG (AM)](/WNEG_(AM)), broadcasting at 93.1 FM, originates from Toccoa. Its first broadcast dates back to 1956.

Town mall

The [Stephens County Courthouse](/Stephens_County_Courthouse_(Georgia)) in downtown Toccoa

The heart of downtown Toccoa, located near [the courthouse](/Stephens_County_Courthouse_(Georgia)) and the train depot that connects to Atlanta, experienced a period of significant commercial activity from the 1950s through the 1980s. This era saw the downtown area transform into a bustling "mall," attracting throngs of shoppers daily. Several prominent national retail chains, including the [Belk](/Belk) Gallant department store, were situated in downtown Toccoa during this time.

In the early 1960s, a nationwide trend emerged where local downtown businesses faced intense competition from burgeoning large shopping malls, leading to the decline of many small businesses. In response to these economic challenges, Toccoa, like numerous other towns, constructed concrete canopies and closed off streets to create pedestrian malls. However, within a decade, it became evident that rather than revitalizing businesses and fostering a positive downtown image, these canopies had inadvertently accelerated the district's decline.

When the Belk Gallant department store announced its relocation to a four-lane thoroughfare known as Big A, community leaders mobilized, forming Main Street Toccoa in 1990. In 1991, the Georgia Department of Community Affairs Resource Team recommended the removal of the canopies and the reopening of streets to vehicular traffic. Despite this recommendation, the project languished for many years without adequate support.

During this period, Main Street Toccoa implemented numerous changes and improvements to the downtown mall area. Brick pavers were installed, and trees were planted. However, the canopies themselves began to deteriorate, and no funding materialized for their repair. Throughout this time, businesses continued to struggle, and many buildings fell into disrepair, remaining vacant.

Eventually, with growing community backing, approval was granted to commence the canopy removal project. Efforts that galvanized public support included county-wide public surveys, a market study conducted by the University of Georgia, a UGA design charrette, and renderings of individual buildings without the canopies, provided by the GA Trust for Historic Preservation and UGA Community Design Planning and Preservation. To secure the necessary funding for the project, Toccoa collaborated with six state agencies—the Appalachian Regional Commission, Georgia Department of Community Affairs, One Georgia Authority, United States Department of Agriculture, and Georgia Department of Transportation—which collectively provided $1.3 million. This was supplemented by an additional $552,000 in local funding.

Downtown renovation construction phase, 2007

During the canopy removal and street reopening initiative, private sector interest in downtown Toccoa experienced a noticeable increase. By 2008, the downtown area saw 33 storefronts renovated, under the guidance of the Georgia Mountains Regional Development Center Historic Preservation Planner. This period also marked the establishment of 11 new businesses, the creation of 17 new jobs, the retention of 28 part-time jobs and 68 full-time equivalent jobs, and a substantial private investment of $3.5 million. Main Street was subsequently reopened to vehicular traffic.

The Currahee Military Museum, featured on the PBS series *GA Traveler* and recognized by *Blue Ridge Mountain* magazine as one of the premier museums on the East Coast, stands as another testament to downtown's ongoing resurgence. Located within the restored historic [train depot](/Toccoa_station), the museum showcases an extensive exhibit of memorabilia from [506th Easy Company](/506th_Infantry_Regiment_(United_States)). This World War II paratrooper company gained widespread recognition through the popular HBO miniseries [Band of Brothers](/Band_of_Brothers_(TV_miniseries)). The depot itself, which houses the museum, underwent a recent restoration to its pre-1940s appearance.

Previously utilized as a maintenance and storage area by Norfolk Southern, the depot was transformed into a publicly accessible building. It now serves as the home for the Chamber of Commerce, a Welcome Center, the Stephens County Historical Society Museum, the Currahee Military Museum, and Amtrak services. Funding for this transformative project was secured through Transportation Enhancement Activity and GDOT grants totaling $400,000, complemented by $100,000 in local funding and over $500,000 in private investment.

Stephens County Courthouse in downtown Toccoa

The Stephens County Courthouse, a prominent landmark in downtown Toccoa, further enhances the city's appeal as a destination in Northeast Georgia.

Sister cities

Toccoa does not currently maintain an active [sister city](/Sister_city) program. A sister city relationship was established with [Meßstetten](/Me%C3%9Fstetten), [Germany](/Germany), during the 1970s, but this affiliation has not been renewed. &#91;39&#93;

